## Task 5 Types of Encryption

Symmetric Encryption
Same key for encryption and decryption.
Challenge: secure key distribution.
Examples:
- DES (56-bit, broken in 1999).
- 3DES (168-bit, deprecated in 2019).
- AES (128/192/256-bit, current standard).
Asymmetric Encryption
Uses public key (encrypt) + private key (decrypt).
Examples: RSA, Diffie-Hellman, ECC.
- RSA: 2048-bit minimum, up to 4096-bit.
- ECC: shorter keys with equivalent security (256-bit ECC ≈ 3072-bit RSA).
Based on one-way mathematical problems (easy forward, infeasible reverse).
Public key shared openly; private key kept secret.
Summary of New Terms:
Alice & Bob: fictional parties in cryptography examples.
- Symmetric encryption: same key for both processes.
- Asymmetric encryption: public/private key pair.

